# Load libraries
library(Seurat)
library(clustree)
library(patchwork)

outdir <- "/mnt/S/People/Cassie/scRNAseq_training/results/"

Load data.

# vector of paths to all sample directories
datadirs <- list.files(path = "/mnt/S/People/Cassie/scRNAseq_training/data/project4/data/", full.names = TRUE)

# get the sample names
# replace underscores with hyphen to correctly extract sample names later on
names(datadirs) <- basename(datadirs) |> gsub("_", "-", x = _) 

# for now, we only take the HPV negative and cervical cancer samples (n=4)
datadirs <- datadirs[c("N-HPV-NEG-1", "N-HPV-NEG-2", "SCC-4", "SCC-5")]

# create a large sparse matrix from all count data
sparse_matrix <- Seurat::Read10X(data.dir = datadirs)

# create a seurat object from sparse matrix
seu <- Seurat::CreateSeuratObject(counts = sparse_matrix,
                                  project = "CervicalCancerStudy")

Question

  • How many cells are in this data set?
  • Answer: ~40,000
dim(seu@assays$RNA$counts)[2]
## [1] 36535

QC and Filtering

DefaultAssay(seu) <- "RNA"
Seurat::Idents(seu) <- seu$orig.ident

# nCount - UMI/read counts per cell
# nFeature - Genes expressed per cell
Seurat::VlnPlot(seu, features = c("nCount_RNA",
                                  "nFeature_RNA"))

Plot mt, ribosomal and globin gene expression.

# mitochondrial genes
seu <- Seurat::PercentageFeatureSet(seu, 
                                    pattern = "^MT-", 
                                    col.name = "percent.mito")

# ribosomal genes
seu <- Seurat::PercentageFeatureSet(seu, 
                                    pattern = "^RP[SL]",
                                    col.name = "percent.ribo")

# hemoglobin genes (but not HBP)
seu <- Seurat::PercentageFeatureSet(seu,
                                    pattern = "^HB[^(P)]",
                                    col.name = "percent.globin")

Seurat::VlnPlot(seu, features = c("percent.mito",
                                  "percent.ribo",
                                  "percent.globin"))

Filtering

Questions

  • Is there evidence of dying cells in the dataset?
  • How can we filter out dying cells?
  • How does your strategy compare with what was done in the two papers?

Paper 1:

  • With counts or genes outside the limits: mean value +/- 2-fold of standard deviation
  • 10% mt

Paper 2:

  • mt < 20%
  • min features > 200
  • max feature - didnt have a threshold

Bonus questions:

  • Why do you think paper 2 chose not to remove potential doublets?
  • Answer: Tight distributions for n_counts and n_features -> little evidence of potential doublets
  • Do you think paper 1 or paper 2 chose a better threshold for mt percentage?
  • Answer: Paper 2. Based on the distribution of percent.mito, 10% seems too low. Also mt can sometimes be highly expressed in tumour cells so its better to be conservative.
# Rm low features

Integration

Question:

  • How can we correct for batch effects?
  • Answer: Integration
seu <- readRDS(paste0(outdir,"integrated.umap.clustered.RDS"))
list <- SplitObject(seu, split.by = "orig.ident")
features <- SelectIntegrationFeatures(object.list = list)
list <- PrepSCTIntegration(object.list = list, anchor.features = features)
anchors <- FindIntegrationAnchors(object.list = list, normalization.method = "SCT",
    anchor.features = features)
seu <- IntegrateData(anchorset = anchors, normalization.method = "SCT")

UMAP on integrated data

Question:

  • How does the UMAP compare pre vs post integration?
  • Answer: Integration has reduced the clustering by sample
seu <- RunPCA(seu, verbose = FALSE, npcs = 100)
Seurat::ElbowPlot(seu, ndims = 100) +
  ggplot2::geom_vline(xintercept = 50, linetype = "dashed", color = "red", linewidth = 1)

seu <- RunUMAP(seu, reduction = "pca", dims = 1:50, verbose = FALSE)
Seurat::DimPlot(seu, reduction = "umap", group.by = "orig.ident")

Question:

  • Which major cell types are you expecting for this dataset?

Answer:

Looking at the papers we expect,

  • Epithelial
  • Immune
  • Stromal (endothelial, fibroplasms, smooth muscle)

Question:

  • Which marker genes could we use for annotation?
  • Answer: see figure 1c. Here I chose a few cell types and markers.
DefaultAssay(seu) <- "SCT"

my_marker_genes = list(
    "NK_T cells" = c('CD3E', 'CD3D','NKG7'),
    "B cells" = c('CD79A'),
    "Epithelial" = c("EPCAM","KLF5")
)
for(ct in names(my_marker_genes)){
  p <- Seurat::FeaturePlot(seu, my_marker_genes[[ct]], ncol=2)
  print(p)
}

p <-DotPlot(seu,
                       features =my_marker_genes, 
                       group.by = "integrated_snn_res.0.03"
            )

p

Answer:
